<CaseStudy
  title="Analytical Method Development in cGMP Manufacturing"
  subtitle="Anant Pharmaceuticals · Associate Scientist I, Analytical Development · July 2022 – May 2023"
  tags={['cGMP', 'HPLC', 'GC-FID', 'Method Validation', 'FDA Audit Readiness', 'ICH Q2(R1)']}
  year="2022 – 2023"
  description="Analytical method development and validation in cGMP manufacturing at Anant Pharmaceuticals. HPLC-UV/Vis, GC-FID, ICH Q2(R1) compliance, FDA audit readiness. Aashni Khurana's experience in pharmaceutical QC."
  prevStudy={{ title: 'DMDS–Albumin Protein Binding', href: '/case-studies/dmds-experimental' }}
>

  <p>
    My first scientific job was at Anant Pharmaceuticals, an Active Pharmaceutical Ingredient (API) manufacturing site in Karnal, India. I joined as a summer intern in July 2022 and spent my first weeks on the production floor: capsule and tablet formulation, coating operations, cough syrup batching. It is a useful place to start for an analytical chemist, because you spend a month measuring things only after you have watched them being made.
  </p>

  <p>
    I converted to Associate Scientist I in Analytical Development shortly after, and the work was current Good Manufacturing Practice (cGMP) from day one. Batch-release testing for APIs bound for regulated markets, where every assay, every chromatogram, and every logbook entry has to survive U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) or European Medicines Agency (EMA) inspection. I learned analytical chemistry the way it is actually practiced in industry: not as isolated experiments but as a continuous pipeline of batches, each one a product that has to ship, each one a decision about whether a drug is fit for human use.
  </p>

  <p>
    Across eleven months in the analytical group, I ran release and in-process testing on 50+ API and drug-product batches per week using High-Performance Liquid Chromatography (HPLC)-UV/Vis, Gas Chromatography with Flame Ionization Detection (GC-FID), and UV-Vis spectroscopy, generating over 600 Certificates of Analysis that moved product from manufacturing to dispatch. I supported International Council for Harmonisation (ICH) Q1A stability and impurity profiling for eight drug substance programs, two of which I validated analytical methods for from scratch: two Reversed-Phase High-Performance Liquid Chromatography (RP-HPLC) methods developed, qualified, and documented per ICH Q2(R1), covering specificity, linearity, accuracy, precision, Limit of Detection/Limit of Quantitation (LOD/LOQ), and robustness. I also led Installation Qualification/Operational Qualification/Performance Qualification (IQ/OQ/PQ) qualification on three HPLC and GC systems, bringing new instruments from uncrated to production-ready, and authored the change control and deviation records required under 21 CFR Part 11.
  </p>

  <!-- TODO: Aashni — add an HPLC instrument or lab photo if available: <div class="cs-image-wrap"><img src="/images/..." alt="..." /><p class="cs-caption">...</p></div> -->

  <p>
    The work I am most proud of from that period was the audit-readiness. I supported two FDA audit-preparation reviews for the site, walking through Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs), logbooks, deviation records, and data-integrity trails to flag issues before inspectors could. Both reviews closed with zero critical findings. That outcome is not glamorous (audit-readiness never is), but it is the kind of result that keeps a site operational and patients supplied. It is also where I learned that scientific rigor and regulatory rigor are the same thing viewed from different angles.
  </p>

  <p>
    I left Anant wanting to move further upstream: from releasing drugs to helping design the methods that measure them, and eventually to helping design the drugs themselves.
  </p>

